# Two storage formats, always parse both

Cursor writes image attachments on a bubble's JSON value in **two**
shapes and either, both, or neither may appear on any given bubble:

- **Modern** — `bubble.context.selectedImages` entries of the form
  `{uuid, path, dimension: {width, height}, loadedAt, addedWithoutMention}`,
  where `path` is an absolute filesystem path like
  `<cursor_root>/User/workspaceStorage/<workspace_id>/images/image-<uuid>.png`.
- **Legacy** — top-level `bubble.images` entries of the form
  `{uuid, dimension: {width, height}, data: {"0": byte, "1": byte, ...}}`,
  where `data` is a serialized `Uint8Array` reconstructed as
  `bytes(data[str(i)] for i in range(len(data)))`.

A single call to
`cursor_view.images.parse_bubble_images` walks both shapes and dedups
by `uuid` with first-seen-wins (disk preferred, because a live disk
file is cheaper than parsing the inline byte dict). **Do not**
branch-by-format at the call site or write a second parser that only
looks at one shape; the canonical example is the 22-bubble-wide legacy
corpus on my install that modern builds might re-emit with
`selectedImages` alongside the legacy `images` array.

Motivating source: `cursor_view/images/refs.py::parse_bubble_images`.

# MIME by magic bytes, never by extension

`cursor_view/images/loading.py::_sniff_mime` checks a 3-to-12-byte
prefix against the magic signatures of PNG (8 bytes), JPEG (3 bytes),
GIF (6 bytes), and WEBP (the split `RIFF` at offsets 0-3 plus `WEBP`
at offsets 8-11 is intentional because bytes 4-7 are the file-size
field, which is content-dependent). The "first 16 bytes" figure only
appears in the unknown-magic debug-log slice (`data[:16]`) -- it is
not the recognition window. **Never** trust a filename extension for
MIME: Cursor's `.png`-suffixed files have in the wild carried JPEG
payloads, and the browser will refuse to render a mismatch.

The module is stdlib-only on purpose. Do not reach for `imghdr`,
`python-magic`, or Pillow -- those dependencies bloat the PyInstaller
bundle and import-time cost, which
[`python-standards.mdc`](python-standards.mdc) explicitly calls out. If
a new format becomes common enough that magic-byte sniffing needs to
grow, add another prefix check inside `_sniff_mime`; do not swap the
strategy.

# BLOBs live only in `chat_image`

Image bytes live in the `chat_image` content table (see
[`sqlite-cursor-db.mdc`](sqlite-cursor-db.mdc)) and **nowhere else**
inside the chat-index cache:

- Not in `chat_search_text` / `chat_search_fts`. Adding base64 or raw
  bytes to those tables breaks FTS5 tokenization and inflates the
  per-chat text blob we actually want tokenized.
- Not in `cursor_view.cache.delta.composer_rows._composer_hash`. The
  source-row hash produced by
  `cursor_view/cache/diff/hashing.py::_hash_value` already flips when
  a bubble's `images` / `context.selectedImages` fields change, so
  images-as-hash-input is redundant; more importantly, folding
  megabyte-scale bytes into the watermark column destroys the point of
  a lightweight drift sentinel.

The table's `(session_id, position, image_index)` primary key is
`UNIQUE`, but `(session_id, uuid)` is intentionally **not**: the same
image uuid can legitimately appear on multiple turns (Cursor
represents repeat attachments as two bubbles pointing at the same
uuid), so `ChatIndex.get_image` uses `LIMIT 1` and trusts that any
matching row's bytes are identical. Do not add a `UNIQUE` constraint
on `(session_id, uuid)` or repeat-attachment chats will fail to
insert.

# Bytes flow through dedicated paths, never through `GET /api/chat/<id>`

The chat-detail JSON payload
(`ChatIndex.get_chat(session_id, include_image_bytes=False)` is the
default) carries per-image **metadata only**: `{uuid, mime_type,
width, height}`. Bytes reach consumers via exactly two paths:

1. `GET /api/chat/<session_id>/image/<image_uuid>` — the dedicated
   HTTP route served by `cursor_view/routes.py::get_chat_image`,
   which hits `ChatIndex.get_image` and responds with
   `Content-Type: <mime>` plus
   `Cache-Control: private, max-age=31536000, immutable`. The frontend
   gallery (`frontend/src/components/chat-detail/MessageImageGallery.js`)
   builds `<img src="...">` URLs against this route.
2. `ChatIndex.get_chat(..., include_image_bytes=True)` — the opt-in
   mode the export routes flip on so Markdown / JSON / HTML renderers
   can inline `data:<mime>;base64,...` URIs into the written file.
   `cursor_view/chat_index/rows.py::_fetch_images_for_session` owns
   the base64 encoding; nothing else in the code base should be
   calling `base64.b64encode` on image data.

Do not add a third path that embeds base64 into the chat-detail JSON
-- that undoes the entire point of the route split (a chat with many
images would blow up the first page load).

# Markdown export: blank line between `<img>` tags and `---`

`cursor_view/export/markdown.py::_markdown_message_lines` emits a
blank line between the last `<img>` and the trailing `---` thematic
break **only when a message carries images**. Without that blank,
CommonMark parsers consume the `<img>` as a paragraph whose following
`---` is either a setext-H2 underline or literal dashes, so users see
the thematic break rendered as a giant page-break heading or as three
stray dashes instead of a horizontal rule. Text-only messages already
have the required blank (the ``content.rstrip() + ""`` pair above the
image block), so the conditional append is strictly image-specific:
append `""` when `_render_message_images_markdown` returns a non-empty
list, leave the sequence untouched when it returns empty so text-only
output stays byte-identical.

The HTML exporter does not need this discipline because it is not
parsed as CommonMark -- `_render_message_images_html` emits a
`<div class="message-images">` container directly. Any future
text-format exporter that emits thematic breaks around image markers
must apply the same blank-line discipline before the break. Regression
guard: `tests/test_chat_index_images.py::MarkdownExportImageTest`
pins both the `<img … />\n\n---` shape (present) and the direct-concat
`<img … />\n---` shape (absent).

# Graceful skip on missing / malformed sources

Image materialization is **not** fail-fast. When
`cursor_view.images.load_image_bytes` cannot produce bytes -- missing
on-disk file (`OSError`), malformed inline byte dict
(`KeyError` / `TypeError` / `ValueError`), or an unknown
`source_kind` on a round-tripped transport dict -- it logs a lazy
`%s`-style warning and returns `None`.
`cursor_view/chat_index/rows.py::_insert_chat_images` skips the
corresponding image, the owning message still lands in
`chat_message`, and no exception propagates.

This is deliberate graceful degradation, **not** a
[`known-bugs.mdc`](known-bugs.mdc) `TODO(bug):`. Do not add a
`TODO(bug):` marker to this path and do not introduce a raise-on-miss
variant; one broken attachment must never drop a whole message.

Lazy `%s`-style logging is required per
[`python-standards.mdc`](python-standards.mdc) so that a disabled log
level does not pay the cost of formatting the missing file's path.

# Canonical examples

- `cursor_view/images/refs.py` — dataclass + two-format parser + dedup.
- `cursor_view/images/loading.py` — magic-byte MIME sniff + graceful
  skip loader.
- `cursor_view/chat_index/rows.py::_insert_chat_images` /
  `_fetch_images_for_session` — the only places that materialize or
  encode image BLOBs.
- `cursor_view/routes.py::get_chat_image` — the dedicated HTTP route.
- `cursor_view/export/markdown.py::_render_message_images_markdown` /
  `cursor_view/export/html.py::_render_message_images_html` /
  `cursor_view/routes.py::export_chat` (JSON branch, which flips
  `include_image_bytes=True` and emits the per-image `data_uri`
  through `messages_for_json_export`) — the three consumers that
  inline base64 data URIs.
- `frontend/src/components/chat-detail/MessageImageGallery.js` and its
  sibling `frontend/src/components/chat-detail/ImageLightboxModal.js` —
  the frontend consumers of image bytes. Both point `<img src>` at the
  dedicated `GET /api/chat/<session_id>/image/<image_uuid>` route rather
  than base64-inlining into the chat-detail JSON. The modal opens
  full-size on thumbnail click and reuses the browser cache from the
  gallery's already-fetched thumbnails, so no second network hit.
